{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"685c858b-3dfa-4810-b6c7-e932306608e7","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **reinstalls** the workloads you already have *at their current versions*. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, `update` is the right choice:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, verify the MAUI workload is present with `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bbee822a-703a-4512-8dc9-1bbf88cb736b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":248,"requestId":"0454:31BA5F:A8E25D:C1631A:6A027963"},"id":"c8f17135-1324-423a-84c0-d21494ce18b8","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:50:50.823Z","parentId":"7fa5da5c-0290-4252-97d0-86ba8fec3de2"}
